one"},"cache":{"type":"none"},"title":"RPI","header":{"text":{"id":"area","table":"views","field":"area","label":"","relationship":"none","group_type":"group","content":"If you've never heard of the RPI, it stands for <strong>Ratings Percentage Index<\/strong>, and it's a system primarily used by the NCAA to qualitatively rank college basketball teams. It evaluates a team's success by factoring not only the team's record but the strength of that team's schedule and its opponents' schedules.\r\n\r\nThe basic formula goes like this:\r\n25% = Your team's record as a percentage of games won (PCT)<BR>\r\n50% = The win-loss percentage of the teams you have faced so far, collectively (This is the strength of your schedule, abbreviated below as SOS), and<BR>\r\n25% = The win-loss percentage of all the teams who have played all the teams you have played against -- that is, collectively, your opponents' strength of schedule (OSOS).<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nI've actually been doing this for several years but it was more of a hobby and, until last year, I had never officially published these numbers on the NYACSL website. <strong>NOTE: These rankings have absolutely no relevance on the standings or determining which teams advance to the post-season.<\/strong> It's just an interesting resource for all who are statistically-minded to enjoy.\r\n\r\n","format":"1"}},"header_format":"1","header_empty":0,"items_per_page":0,"offset":0,"use_pager":false,"pager_element":0,"style_plugin":"table","style_options":{"grouping":"","override":1,"sticky":0,"order":"desc","columns":{"field_season_rpi1000_value":"field_season_rpi1000_value","field_team_reference_for_stats_nid":"field_team_reference_for_stats_nid"},"info":{"field_season_rpi1000_value":{"sortable":0,"separator":""},"field_team_reference_for_stats_nid":{"separator":""}},"default":"field_season_rpi1000_value"},"row_plugin":"fields","row_options":[],"query":{"type":"views_query","options":[]}}},"plugin_type":"display","options":{"title":"RPI","enabled":true,"display_comment":"","css_class":"","display_description":"","use_ajax":false,"hide_attachment_summary":false,"items_per_page":0,"offset":0,"use_pager":false,"use_more":false,"use_more_always":false,"use_more_text":"more","link_display":"","link_url":"","group_by":false,"field_language":"***CURRENT_LANGUAGE***","field_language_add_to_query":1,"access":{"type":"none"},"cache":{"type":"none"},"query":{"type":"views_query","options":[]},"exposed_form":{"type":"basic","options":[]},"pager":{"type":"full","options":[]},"style_plugin":"table","style_options":{"grouping":"","override":1,"sticky":0,"order":"desc","columns":{"field_season_rpi1000_value":"field_season_rpi1000_value","field_team_reference_for_stats_nid":"field_team_reference_for_stats_nid"},"info":{"field_season_rpi1000_value":{"sortable":0,"separator":""},"field_team_reference_for_stats_nid":{"separator":""}},"default":"field_season_rpi1000_value"},"row_plugin":"fields","row_options":[],"exposed_block":false,"header":{"text":{"id":"area","table":"views","field":"area","label":"","relationship":"none","group_type":"group","content":"If you've never heard of the RPI, it stands for <strong>Ratings Percentage Index<\/strong>, and it's a system primarily used by the NCAA to qualitatively rank college basketball teams. It evaluates a team's success by factoring not only the team's record but the strength of that team's schedule and its opponents' schedules.\r\n\r\nThe basic formula goes like this:\r\n25% = Your team's record as a percentage of games won (PCT)<BR>\r\n50% = The win-loss percentage of the teams you have faced so far, collectively (This is the strength of your schedule, abbreviated below as SOS), and<BR>\r\n25% = The win-loss percentage of all the teams who have played all the teams you have played against -- that is, collectively, your opponents' strength of schedule (OSOS).<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nI've actually been doing this for several years but it was more of a hobby and, until last year, I had never officially published these numbers on the NYACSL website. you've never heard of the RPI, it stands for <strong>Ratings Percentage Index<\/strong>, and it's a system primarily used by the NCAA to qualitatively rank college basketball teams. It evaluates a team's success by factoring not only the team's record but the strength of that team's schedule and its opponents' schedules.\r\n\r\nThe basic formula goes like this:\r\n25% = Your team's record as a percentage of games won (PCT)<BR>\r\n50% = The win-loss percentage of the teams you have faced so far, collectively (This is the strength of your schedule, abbreviated below as SOS), and<BR>\r\n25% = The win-loss percentage of all the teams who have played all the teams you have played against -- that is, collectively, your opponents' strength of schedule (OSOS).<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nI've actually been doing this for several years but it was more of a hobby and, until last year, I had never officially published these numbers on the NYACSL website. you've never heard of the RPI, it stands for <strong>Ratings Percentage Index<\/strong>, and it's a system primarily used by the NCAA to qualitatively rank college basketball teams. It evaluates a team's success by factoring not only the team's record but the strength of that team's schedule and its opponents' schedules.\r\n\r\nThe basic formula goes like this:\r\n25% = Your team's record as a percentage of games won (PCT)<BR>\r\n50% = The win-loss percentage of the teams you have faced so far, collectively (This is the strength of your schedule, abbreviated below as SOS), and<BR>\r\n25% = The win-loss percentage of all the teams who have played all the teams you have played against -- that is, collectively, your opponents' strength of schedule (OSOS).<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nI've actually been doing this for several years but it was more of a hobby and, until last year, I had never officially published these numbers on the NYACSL website. <strong>NOTE: These rankings have absolutely no relevance on the standings or determining which teams advance to the post-season.<\/strong> It's just an interesting resource for all who are statistically-minded to
